  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you sort a collection in Java?",
  "response": "In Java, you can sort a collection using several methods depending on the type of collection and the sorting criteria. Here are the most common approaches:\n\n### 1. **Sorting a `List` (e.g., `ArrayList`, `LinkedList`)**\n   - **Using `Collections.sort()`**:  \n     The `Collections.sort()` method sorts a `List` in natural order (i.e., ascending order for numbers, lexicographical order for strings).\n     ```java\n     import java.util.Collections;\n     import java.util.ArrayList;\n     import java.util.List;\n\n     public class Main {\n         public static void main(String[] args) {\n             List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();\n             numbers.add(5);\n             numbers.add(1);\n             numbers.add(3);\n\n             Collections.sort(numbers); // Sorts in natural order\n             System.out.println(numbers); // Output: [1, 3, 5]\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n   - **Using a Custom Comparator**:  \n     If you want to sort with a custom order or criteria, pass a `Comparator` to `Collections.sort()`.\n     ```java\n     import java.util.Collections;\n     import java.util.ArrayList;\n     import java.util.List;\n     import java.util.Comparator;\n\n     public class Main {\n         public static void main(String[] args) {\n             List<String> words = new ArrayList<>();\n             words.add(\"apple\");\n             words.add(\"banana\");\n             words.add(\"cherry\");\n\n             // Sort in reverse order\n             Collections.sort(words, Comparator.reverseOrder());\n             System.out.println(words); // Output: [cherry, banana, apple]\n\n             // Sort by string length\n             Collections.sort(words, Comparator.comparing(String::length));\n             System.out.println(words); // Output: [apple, cherry, banana]\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n   - **Using `List.sort()`**:  \n     The `List` interface also provides a `sort()` method that works similarly.\n     ```java\n     List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();\n     numbers.add(5);\n     numbers.add(1);\n     numbers.add(3);\n\n     numbers.sort(Comparator.naturalOrder()); // Sorts in natural order\n     System.out.println(numbers); // Output: [1, 3, 5]\n     ```\n\n### 2. **Sorting an Array**\n   - **Using `Arrays.sort()`**:  \n     For arrays, use the `Arrays.sort()` method.\n     ```java\n     import java.util.Arrays;\n\n     public class Main {\n         public static void main(String[] args) {\n             int[] numbers = {5, 1, 3};\n             Arrays.sort(numbers); // Sorts in natural order\n             System.out.println(Arrays.toString(numbers)); // Output: [1, 3, 5]\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n   - **Using a Custom Comparator for Object Arrays**:  \n     For arrays of objects, you can pass a `Comparator` to `Arrays.sort()`.\n     ```java\n     import java.util.Arrays;\n     import java.util.Comparator;\n\n     public class Main {\n         public static void main(String[] args) {\n             String[] words = {\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"};\n\n             // Sort by string length\n             Arrays.sort(words, Comparator.comparing(String::length));\n             System.out.println(Arrays.toString(words)); // Output: [apple, cherry, banana]\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n### 3. **Sorting a `Set` or `Map`**\n   - **Convert to a Sorted Collection**:  \n     Sets and Maps are inherently unordered. To sort them, convert them to a sorted collection like a `TreeSet` or `TreeMap`, which automatically sorts elements in natural order or by a custom `Comparator`.\n     ```java\n     import java.util.Set;\n     import java.util.TreeSet;\n\n     public class Main {\n         public static void main(String[] args) {\n             Set<Integer> numbers = new TreeSet<>();\n             numbers.add(5);\n             numbers.add(1);\n             numbers.add(3);\n\n             System.out.println(numbers); // Output: [1, 3, 5]\n\n             // Custom Comparator for TreeSet\n             Set<String> words = new TreeSet<>(Comparator.reverseOrder());\n             words.add(\"apple\");\n             words.add(\"banana\");\n             words.add(\"cherry\");\n\n             System.out.println(words); // Output: [cherry, banana, apple]\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n### 4. **Sorting with Streams**\n   - **Using `Stream.sorted()`**:  \n     If you're working with streams, you can use the `sorted()` method to sort elements.\n     ```java\n     import java.util.List;\n     import java.util.stream.Collectors;\n\n     public class Main {\n         public static void main(String[] args) {\n             List<Integer> numbers = List.of(5, 1, 3);\n\n             List<Integer> sortedNumbers = numbers.stream()\n                                                  .sorted()\n                                                  .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n             System.out.println(sortedNumbers); // Output: [1, 3, 5]\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n   - **Using a Custom Comparator with Streams**:\n     ```java\n     List<String> words = List.of(\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\");\n\n     List<String> sortedWords = words.stream()\n                                     .sorted(Comparator.comparing(String::length))\n                                     .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n     System.out.println(sortedWords); // Output: [apple, cherry, banana]\n     ```\n\n### Summary\n- Use `Collections.sort()` or `List.sort()` for `List` collections.\n- Use `Arrays.sort()` for arrays.\n- Use `TreeSet` or `TreeMap` for sorted `Set` or `Map` collections.\n- Use `Stream.sorted()` for sorting with streams.\n\nBy choosing the appropriate method based on your data structure and sorting requirements, you can easily sort collections in Java.",
